memories.title: ChCl:EG:Gly:Urea:ZnCl₂ (1:2:1:1:0.5) Achieves 1.0 g/L Noble Metal Solubility at 25°C
memories.description: A 5-component DES with choline chloride, ethylene glycol, glycerol, urea, and zinc chloride in a 1:2:1:1:0.5 molar ratio dissolves noble metals at 1.0 g/L at 25°C.
memories.content: The formulation ChCl:EG:Gly:Urea:ZnCl₂ (1:2:1:1:0.5) successfully formed a liquid DES at room temperature, confirming compatibility among all five components. Under experimental conditions of 25°C, this DES achieved a noble metal solubility of 1.0 g/L. The inclusion of ZnCl₂ as a Lewis acid appears to enable limited oxidative dissolution despite ambient temperature operation.

memories.title: Urea- and Polyol-Based HBDs Enable 5-Component DES Formation at 25°C
memories.description: Combining urea with multiple polyols (ethylene glycol, glycerol) in a multi-HBD system supports eutectic formation in complex DES at 25°C.
memories.content: This DES utilized three hydrogen bond donors—urea, ethylene glycol, and glycerol—combined with choline chloride and ZnCl₂, forming a stable liquid phase at 25°C. The synergistic hydrogen bonding network between amide (urea) and hydroxyl-rich polyols likely contributed to sufficient melting point depression for ambient DES formation, even in a high-component system.

memories.title: ZnCl₂ Addition (0.5 Molar Ratio) Insufficient for High Noble Metal Solubility in ChCl-Based DES
memories.description: Including ZnCl₂ at a 0.5 molar ratio relative to choline chloride yields only moderate solubility (1.0 g/L) for noble metals despite successful DES formation.
memories.content: Although ZnCl₂ was added as a Lewis acidic promoter for noble metal coordination and oxidative dissolution, its concentration at a 0.5 molar ratio did not significantly enhance solubility beyond 1.0 g/L. This suggests that either higher ZnCl₂ ratios or stronger oxidizing agents may be required to improve performance in choline chloride–based multi-component DES systems. ```
